The latest design of the legend in technology, Inrut, is a company that builds the platform with an open source of Berners-Lie Solid.
Solid allows consumers to choose where to store their data and which people are allowed to access certain information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company Burners-Lee, the intention behind Inrut is "worldly dominance".
"We need to do it now," he said regarding the undertaking.
"This is a historic moment."
The application uses Solid technology that allows people to create their own “online personal data storage facility” or pod.
It contains lists, lists of tasks, calendar, music library and other personal and professional tools.
It looks like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify that are available through each browser, and at the same time there are all of them at the same time.
The unique thing about the personal data store is that the user determines who has access to what information.
The company calls it "a given authority for personal data."
The idea for Inrut, according to company CEO John Bruce, is to invest the company resources, processes and adequate skills to help Solid become accessible to everyone.
Currently, the company consists of Berners-Ley, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several developers, concluded a contract for work on the project, and a group of volunteer programmers.
Since this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralisation applications using the tools available on the Inrut website.
Burners-Li said that he and his team don't talk to Facebook and Google about whether to make a complete change, or not, when all their business models are completely updated in one night.
"We do not want permission from them."
In a post in Medium on Saturday, Berners-Li wrote that the mission of Inrut was to provide energy for trade and ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on Solid.
In 1994, Burners-Li transformed the Internet when he created the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Technical Institute.
In recent months, Burners-Li has had a strong influence on the debate about net neutrality.
Although Inrut started, Berners-Lee will remain founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, Web Foundation and Open Data Institute.
"I am extremely optimistic about this new era on the Internet," Burners-Li added.
Bernard Van: In memory of the priest honored by the cross of Victoria during World War I
They have been recorded for 100 years in the native city of the only Anglican priest, honored by the cross of Victoria for his participation in wartime activities during World War I.
Lieutenant Colonel Bernard Van won the award on September 29, 1918, at the attack of Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
Four days later, however, he was killed by a sniper without realizing he was honored with Britain's highest military honour.
A memorial was opened on Saturday by both his grandchildren on a parade in Rusden, Northamptonshire.
One of his grandchildren, Michael Van, said it was "extremely symbolic" to have the monument discovered exactly 100 years of his grandfather's case, awarded with a medal.
According to London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Van led his battalion through Canal de Saint-Quentin "in a very dense fog and under heavy shooting from artillery and machine guns."
Later he attacked the fire line and with “incredible courage ” led the building forward before attacking an artillery gun with one hand and killing three of the squad.
Lieutenant Colonel Van was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918 – only a month before the war ended.
Michael Van, 72, said that his grandfather’s actions were “something I know I could never do, but it makes me feel humble. ”
He and his brother, Dr. James Van, set up a wreath after a parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Van said it was "a great honor to participate in the parade" and added "the virtue of the true hero is demonstrated by the support that will be provided to many people."
