Germany rescinds the launch of a new battleship
The latest frigate of the German fleet had to be put into operation in 2014 to replace the aged warships of the Cold War, but this would not take place until at least next year because of the malfunctioning systems and largely growing costs local media reported.
The introduction into operation of Reheinland-Pfalz, the leading ship of the brand new frigates of the Baden-Wuertemberg class, was postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, which quoted an army spokesman as saying.
The vessel had to join the naval forces in 2014, but the problems that arose after its delivery affected the fate of the ambitious project.
The four vessels of Baden-Wuertemberg class ordered by the fleet in 2007 will replace the aged frigates of Bremen class.
Understandably, they will have a powerful gun, a set of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stelt technologies, e.g. reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signals.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods – the latest frigates must be able to be used up to two years before returning to the ports of housing.
However, uninterrupted delays mean that the avant-garde military ships – which are said to allow Germany to demonstrate power beyond the ocean – will already be old when entering operation, notes Die Zeit.
The evil frigate F125 entered the headlines last year when the German fleet officially refused to release the vessel into operation and returned it to the Blohm & Voss Shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the fleet has returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
It is little known about the reasons for the return, but the German media quoted a number of essential "soft and hardware defects" that make the warship unusable if sent to a combat mission.
Software deficiencies are particularly important because the vessels of the Baden-Wuertemberg class will be managed by a crew of about 120 sailors – only half of the crew of older frigates of the Bremen class.
In addition, it appears that the ship is significantly overloaded, reducing its effectiveness and limiting the possibility of the naval forces to add future superstructures.
The 7000-ton "Rheinland-Pfalz" is believed to be twice as heavy as the ships of such class used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to the defective hardware, the cost of the entire project – including the training of the crew – is also becoming a problem.
It is believed to have reached the staggering 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion) – from the initial 2.2 billion euros.
The problems with the latest frigates are becoming particularly important in light of recent warnings that Germany's naval forces are shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German Parliament's Defence Committee, admitted that the fleet was actually "exhausts from ships capable of carrying out missions".
The official said the problem had become greater in time since the old ships were taken out of operation but no new ones were granted.
He complained that no frigate from the Baden-Wuertemberg class could be included in the fleet.
The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
A new study carried out in a mansion in the Scottish mountains aims to identify how bats use the landscape when they hunt.
The hopes are that the discoveries will shed new light on the behavior of the unique flying mammals and will help guide future conservation actions.
The study by scientists from the National Trust of Scotland will follow the common bats as well as brown arrow water nightshades at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in key places in the property to track the activities of the bats during the season.
NHS and volunteers will also conduct mobile research using hand detectors.
The expert sound analysis of all records will identify the frequency of bat sounds and which species issue them.
Then a map of the habitat and a report will be drawn up to create a detailed landscape of their behaviour.
Rob Duir, a natural conservation adviser for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of the management of habitats, e.g. the creation of meadows, as well as the best way to maintain forest areas for bats and other species associated with them.
The population of bats in Scotland and Britain in general decreased significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by the construction activities that affect their shelters and lead to the loss of habitats.
The risk for populations can be caused by wind turbines and lighting, aircraft and some chemical processing of construction materials, as well as domestic cat attacks.
In fact, bats aren't blind.
However, because of their hunting habits at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echo-location techniques to detect insects and obstacles along their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of great importance and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The trust has trained experts carrying out regular studies, inspections of shelters and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even created the first in Scotland and the only special bat reserve in the Threeave estate in the region of Dumfreys and Gallaway, which is home to eight of the ten bat species in Scotland.
The manager of the David Thompson mansion says it's the perfect territory for them.
"Here, in Threave, we have a great field for bats," he noted.
"We have old buildings, many grown trees and completed a suitable habitat.
But there's still a lot more about bats that are not known, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us understand better than what they need to thrive."
He stressed that it is important to check for the presence of bats before property maintenance activities are carried out, as it is possible for the inadvertent destruction of a asylum to kill up to 400 female and young bats, as well as destroy an entire local population.
The blind are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their refuges.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish employee at the Bat Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said: “I still have a lot to learn about our bats and many of our species, because we just don’t know what’s happening to their populations. ”
