Brexit: Britain “will regret forever” that it lost car manufacturers
Britain "will regret forever" if it loses its status as a world leader in the production of cars after Brexit, said Business Secretary Greg Clark.
He added that it was "concerning" that Toyota UK had told the BBC that if Britain left the EU without a deal, it would temporarily stop production at its Burnstone plant near Derby.
"We need a deal," he said.
Japan's car manufacturer said the impact of the border delay in the case of Brexit without a deal could lead to a loss of jobs.
In the Burnstone factory – where the Auris and Avensis models were produced last year – nearly 150 000 cars were produced, 90% of which were exported to the other countries of the European Union.
"My opinion is that if Britain leaves the EU at the end of March, production at our plant will stop," said Marvin Cook, the director of Toyota in Burnstone.
Other UK car manufacturers, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, expressed concerns about leaving the EU without agreement and how cross-border trade will work.
BMW, for example, says they're closing down their mini-model plant in Oxford in a month after Brexit.
The main concerns of car manufacturers are related to the risks of the supply chain in the case of Brexit without a deal.
Toyota's production line is working on the timing principle, with parts arriving every 37 minutes from suppliers both from the UK and from the EU for cars manufactured on request.
If Britain leaves the EU without a deal on 29 March, there may be problems at the border, which, according to industry, could lead to delays and lack of parts.
For Toyota it would be impossible to wait more than a day to fill their inventory at the Darbisher factory, the company said, so production will stop.
Mr. Clark said Teresa May's "chart" plan for future relations with the EU is "precisely calibrated to avoid these checks at the border".
"We need to have a deal. We want to close the best deal that will allow us, as I say, not only to enjoy the current success, but also to be able to grab this opportunity," he said in the program 4's Today's BBC Radio.
"After the claims not only of Toyota, but of other producers, we are absolutely convinced that we should be able to continue to provide successful supply chains."
Toyota cannot say how long production will be stopped, but in the longer term warns that additional costs will reduce the competitiveness of the plant and ultimately lead to job losses.
Peter Cuvalaris, who has worked in Burnston for 24 years and is the founder of the Union Unite at the plant, said that his members are becoming more and more concerned: “From their experience, I think that if these jobs go away, they will never come back.
