Syria is "ready" for refugee returns, foreign minister said
Syria announced that it was ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asked for assistance in the restoration of the country devastated by the war that lasted more than seven years.
Addressing the UN General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Mualem pointed out that the conditions in the country are improving.
"Today the situation is more stable and safe, thanks to the progress we have in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to restore the areas devastated by the terrorists to return them to their normal state.
There are now all conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they were forced to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that affected their daily life and nutrition.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Six more million people still living there need humanitarian help.
Al-Mualem said the Syrian regime would welcome any assistance in the restoration of the devastated state.
But he stressed that conditional support or assistance from countries that financed the rebels would not be accepted.
